<main id="main">

  <section class="section compact">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Contract structure</div>
          <h2>Animal Control depends on multiple agreements</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Beaumont's Animal Control program has historically operated through
        a combination of direct municipal services and contractual relationships.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some agreements allowed Beaumont to provide Animal Control services
        to outside jurisdictions. Other contracts supplied sheltering,
        licensing administration, and supporting services needed by the
        City's own Animal Control operation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Together, these agreements help explain how a relatively small
        municipal field operation has supported both local and, historically,
        regional Animal Control responsibilities.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact alt">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Regional services</div>
          <h2>City of Calimesa</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="change-grid">

        <article class="change-card">
          <h3>Service relationship</h3>

          <p>
            Beaumont provided Animal Control services to the City of
            Calimesa under an intergovernmental contractual relationship.
          </p>

          <p>
            Later official records identify July 1, 2010 as the beginning
            of the service arrangement.
          </p>

          <p>
            The original 2010 agreement has not been located in the
            digital records reviewed for this Intelligence Center.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="change-card">
          <h3>2021–2023 agreement</h3>

          <p>
            In 2021, Beaumont approved a renewed agreement covering
            Animal Control services for Calimesa from July 1, 2021
            through June 30, 2023.
          </p>

          <p>
            The agreement continued an existing relationship rather than
            establishing a new service program.
          </p>

          <p>
            The contractual relationship concluded at the end of the
            2021–2023 term.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside class="verified-panel">
          <div class="verified-title">Calimesa agreement</div>

          <dl>
            <div>
              <dt>Documented service start</dt>
              <dd>July 1, 2010</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Later agreement term</dt>
              <dd>2021–2023</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Service ended</dt>
              <dd>June 30, 2023</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Current status</dt>
              <dd>Concluded</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </aside>

      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Regional partnerships</div>
          <h2>Morongo Band of Mission Indians</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Available City records also document Animal Control agreements
        involving the Morongo Band of Mission Indians.
      </p>

      <p>
        These records provide additional evidence that Beaumont historically
        operated as a regional Animal Control service provider rather than
        limiting all program activity to municipal boundaries.
      </p>

      <p>
        The currently available digital record does not provide the same
        continuous contractual history for the Morongo relationship that is
        available for the later Calimesa service period.
      </p>

      <p>
        Earlier agreements and amendments therefore remain an area where
        additional archival records could strengthen the operational history.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact alt">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Shelter services</div>
          <h2>Ramona Humane Society and Haven Pet Center</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="change-grid">

        <article class="change-card">
          <h3>Ramona Humane Society</h3>

          <p>
            Beaumont has relied on contracted sheltering rather than
            maintaining its own full-service municipal animal shelter.
          </p>

          <p>
            Ramona Humane Society served as a major sheltering partner
            supporting Beaumont Animal Control.
          </p>

          <p>
            In September 2021, Beaumont approved a multi-year shelter
            services agreement with the organization.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="change-card">
          <h3>Haven Pet Center</h3>

          <p>
            The organization later transitioned to the Haven Pet Center name.
          </p>

          <p>
            Beaumont's shelter services relationship continued while the
            contractual structure was adjusted to reflect changing operating
            conditions and available services.
          </p>

          <p>
            One important operational change involved the removal of
            owner-surrender services from Beaumont's contracted shelter model.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside class="verified-panel">
          <div class="verified-title">Shelter model</div>

          <dl>
            <div>
              <dt>City-owned shelter</dt>
              <dd>No</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Service model</dt>
              <dd>Contracted</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Historical provider</dt>
              <dd>Ramona Humane Society</dd>
            </div>

            <div>
              <dt>Current association</dt>
              <dd>Haven Pet Center</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </aside>

      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Licensing administration</div>
          <h2>PetData</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Beaumont has also used an outside provider to support animal
        licensing administration.
      </p>

      <p>
        PetData provides administrative support associated with licensing,
        allowing the City's Animal Control personnel to maintain enforcement
        responsibilities while certain licensing functions are handled
        through a specialized service provider.
      </p>

      <p>
        Licensing is an important component of the broader Animal Control
        system because it supports animal identification, rabies compliance,
        recovery of lost animals, enforcement, and program revenue.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact alt">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Contract categories</div>
          <h2>Three different contractual roles</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="story-grid">

        <article class="story-card">
          <span>1</span>
          <h3>Service Provider</h3>
          <p>
            Beaumont historically received revenue to provide Animal Control
            services to outside jurisdictions such as Calimesa.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="story-card">
          <span>2</span>
          <h3>Service Purchaser</h3>
          <p>
            Beaumont purchases sheltering services from an outside
            organization rather than operating its own full-service shelter.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="story-card">
          <span>3</span>
          <h3>Administrative Support</h3>
          <p>
            Outside providers such as PetData support specialized
            administrative functions while municipal personnel retain
            core enforcement responsibilities.
          </p>
        </article>

      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Financial significance</div>
          <h2>Contracts affect both revenue and expenditures</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Animal Control contracts have affected Beaumont's finances in
        two different directions.
      </p>

      <p>
        Regional service agreements generated revenue for Beaumont when
        the City provided Animal Control services to outside jurisdictions.
      </p>

      <p>
        At the same time, sheltering and administrative contracts represent
        expenditures required to support Beaumont's municipal Animal Control
        program.
      </p>

      <p>
        The conclusion of the Calimesa relationship in 2023 therefore
        represented more than an operational change: it also ended an
        established source of regional service revenue.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact alt">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Evidence gaps</div>
          <h2>Earlier contracts remain incomplete</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The available digital record provides strong documentation for
        several recent agreements but becomes less complete farther back
        in time.
      </p>

      <p>
        In particular, the original 2010 Beaumont-Calimesa agreement has
        not been located in the digital records reviewed to date.
      </p>

      <p>
        Historical Morongo agreements are also less completely represented
        in the currently available digital archive.
      </p>

      <p>
        These gaps are explicitly identified so later archival research
        can expand the record without confusing documented facts with
        assumptions.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section compact">
    <div class="wrap">

      <div class="section-heading">
        <div>
          <div class="eyebrow">Intelligence assessment</div>
          <h2>Contracts are central to the operating model</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Contractual relationships are not peripheral to Beaumont Animal
        Control. They are a defining feature of how the program has operated.
      </p>

      <p>
        Historically, contracts allowed Beaumont to expand outward as a
        regional service provider. Other agreements allowed the City to
        obtain sheltering and administrative capacity without building
        those functions entirely in-house.
      </p>

      <p>
        The result is a hybrid system: municipal personnel perform core
        field and enforcement functions, while outside organizations provide
        specialized services and infrastructure.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

